<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United States gave Somalia weapons that were used to viciously quell an 
insurgency, then provided disaster assistance to the victims the next month, 
the General Accounting Office reported. The congressional watchdog agency found 
that a $1.4-million U.S. shipment of M-16 automatic rifles and 2.3 million 
rounds of ammunition arrived in Somalia in June, 1988, just as the army 
launched massive artillery and aerial shellings to crush a rebellion in the 
north. Then, "starting in August, 1988, the U.S. government responded to the 
emergency with $1.9 million in disaster assistance to help the victims of the 
conflict," the GAO report said. Since the attacks, the Administration has 
suspended further weapons deliveries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
