<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 7; Column 4; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
369 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMENTARY / EXCERPTS; 
</P>
<P>
A MIGHTY BLOW FOR FRIENDLY PERSUASION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By COLMAN McCARTHY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tian An Men Square is converted into the world's largest peace park. Images 
from China are telling the world that nonviolence is effective, both as a 
conviction of the heart and a tactic of the street. The eruption of nonviolent 
disobedience has brought the Chinese dictators to a state of powerless 
confusion that could never have happened as quickly or been as widespread had 
the students chosen guns or bombs. 
</P>
<P>
Without exception, every show of force -- nonviolent or violent force -- has as 
its goal the changing of minds. George Bush sends 2,000 troops to Panama to 
persuade Manuel Noriega to change his mind about ruling his country. Bank 
robbers aim guns at tellers to change their minds about who should own the 
money in the drawer. Mahatma Gandhi fasted to change England's mind about who 
should rule India. 
</P>
<P>
Every conflict or problem, whether among individuals or governments, has been, 
and will be, solved through the exertion of violent or nonviolent force. No 
third way exists. Choosing nonviolent noncooperation, the Chinese students are 
proving the truth of Gandhi's statement: "Government of the people is possible 
only so long as they consent either consciously or unconsciously to be 
governed." 
</P>
<P>
Eleven Latin American dictators were overthrown in this century through 
nonviolent strikes. Armed Philippine guerrillas tried for years to drive out 
the Marcos regime. He was defeated by nonviolent resistance. 
</P>
<P>
What has violence done? Compare El Salvador and Poland. At about the same time 
in the late 1970s, rebels in both countries wanted to change the mind of the 
government. In El Salvador, they attacked with guns. More than 70,000 have been 
killed on all sides. Governance has worsened. In Poland, they attacked with 
moral force. Few have died. Governance has improved. 
</P>
<P>
A massacre of innocents -- the "crackdown" that pessimists say is inevitable -- 
is still possible in China. What isn't possible is that the bravery and wisdom 
of the past two weeks of massive nonviolence can be canceled. The story still 
to be written is how this group of Chinese students came to understand so well 
and so boldly that the strength of truth and justice is superior to the 
weakness of guns and tanks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052589-0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 61492 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 25, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
