736 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
 HINTS FROM HELOISE: SPICES WON'T SPOIL BUT THEY MAY LOSE THEIR POTENCY AS TIME 
GOES BY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: How long can one keep spices in the cupboard? We will be moving 
in the near future and I was wondering if I should throw them all out and start 
anew since I have had some of them for a few years. 
</P>
<P>
 -- JEANNE, Belleville, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR JEANNE: Before you throw away all those spices, check each one for its 
individually strong, full-bodied aroma and a fresh look. Spices will not go bad 
or spoil; instead, they may lose their potency as time goes by. 
</P>
<P>
The oils in spices, which give them their flavor, escape when exposed to heat, 
moisture or air and eventually deteriorate if stored for a long time. This is 
why it is very important not to store any spices near or over areas of 
higher-than-normal heat or humidity such as over or near a stove, sink or 
dishwasher. Also, a good habit to get into is to replace the lid of a spice 
container as soon as you are through with it to keep it fresh. 
</P>
<P>
If you have added a particular spice to a recipe and the food does not taste 
properly seasoned, the spice has probably lost its potency and should then be 
thrown away. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HELOISE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: Here is what I do to remove any lingering odor of oven cleaner: I 
spread a thick layer of newspaper on the floor of the oven and with a spray 
bottle filled with warm water, I spray the top and sides of the oven well. 
After drying the inside of the oven with a clean cloth, I roll up the newspaper 
carefully and discard it. 
</P>
<P>
This removes all of the oven cleaner residue and prevents bad odors when I 
first turn the oven after it's been cleaned. 
</P>
<P>
 -- FRANCES, Delta, Utah 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I have heard of several ways to flour a cake pan. Some say to use 
cocoa powder when baking a chocolate cake and others say to substitute biscuit 
mix for flour for light-colored cakes. I would like to add my method that has 
never failed me. 
</P>
<P>
After greasing the cake pan, I use the mixed dry ingredients of the recipe to 
flour the pan. If I am using a cake mix, I use some of the dry cake mix. When 
doing this, always remember to return any excess dry mix to the mixing bowl and 
proceed with the recipe. 
</P>
<P>
I have never had a problem with a white dusty look on the bottom of any of my 
cakes. 
</P>
<P>
 -- E.L., Norwalk, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I have found a way of cooking pasta without overheating the 
kitchen. 
</P>
<P>
I first boil the water, to which I have added a pinch of salt and a little 
olive oil, then I add the pasta. When the water begins to boil again, I cover 
the cooking pan with its lid and turn off the burner, leaving the pan on the 
same burner for the recommended cooking time without the heat. 
</P>
<P>
After the recommended time I remove the lid and drain the pasta. It always 
turns out just right this way. 
</P>
<P>
 -- LORI, Sacramento, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I recently bought a couple of cast iron skillets. 
</P>
<P>
The saleswoman gave me a tip: She said that after I wash and dry them to put 
them in the oven to dry completely. Moisture can make cast iron deteriorate. 
It's a good idea to place paper towels between the pans when stacking them so 
there's no trapped moisture. 
</P>
<P>
 -- SUSAN, Amarillo, Tex. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I have a hint that saves me a lot of time and irritation from 
chemicals of commercial oven cleaners. 
</P>
<P>
I use baking soda to clean my oven and I even use it around the burners when 
something that was spilled around them has become baked on. I just wet the 
inside of my oven with a wet rag and then sprinkle baking soda around (more 
heavily on soiled areas) and let it set for about 10 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
Then I use a scrubbing pad and all the baked-on mess comes off real easily. If 
there are some bad spots, use extra soda and scrub a little harder. Rinse out 
the oven. It will be sparkling. 
</P>
<P>
 -- BEVERLY, Boardman, Ohio 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: If you happen to break anything that leaves tiny fragments of 
glass all over the floor, here is a great tip that will help pick up all the 
pieces. 
</P>
<P>
I was staying at a cabin on vacation. While doing the dishes I dropped a glass 
and it shattered all over the floor. I looked for a vacuum or broom, but 
couldn't find either. I remembered a tip that my aunt told me many years ago, 
so I tried it. 
</P>
<P>
After picking up the large pieces of glass, I wet a piece of newspaper. I put 
the paper on the tiny bits of glass, lifted the paper and the glass clung to 
the paper. I did this all around to make sure I got all the pieces. 
</P>
<P>
It worked. I never found a piece of glass during my stay there. 
</P>
<P>
 -- JUDY, Reno, Nev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
