</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PITTSBURGH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Allegheny International Inc., maker of Sunbeam and Oster home appliances, today 
said it has stopped pursuing a merger with a subsidiary of the New York 
investment banking firm of Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc. 
</P>
<P>
Allegheny International, which filed for bankruptcy last February, said that it 
does not anticipate achieving expected levels of domestic operating profit for 
fiscal 1989 and that the failure to achieve the profit would prevent the 
merger. 
</P>
<P>
The company had been told by the DLJ subsidiary that the domestic operating 
profit results were critically important to the subsidiary's ability to raise 
the financing required under the merger agreement. 
</P>
<P>
Allegheny International also said it intends to file with the bankruptcy court 
a separate plan of reorganization for its Sunbeam Corp. subsidiary to permit it 
to emerge from bankruptcy in the near future while AI continued its own 
reorganization case. 
</P>
